eet. Born in Wales before the end of World War I, Sleigh moved to New York =
in 1961 when she was in her forties, along with her art critic and curator =
husband Lawrence Alloway. Ortuzar notes that
Sylvia Sleigh: Every leaf is precious is organized around the theme of her =
personal relationships. The earliest work, from 1950, is a dual portrait of=
 herself and her husband. =E2=80=9CI always painted people, and always peop=
le I know,=E2=80=9D the press release quotes Sleigh as saying. The show=E2=
=80=99s title comes from a comment by the artist about the importance of in=
dividuals and individualism: =E2=80=9CEvery leaf, every person is precious =
and should be loved.=E2=80=9D

Sylvia
Sleigh, October: Felicity Rainnie and Paul Rosano (1974)

Sylvia Sleigh,=C2=A0October: Felicity Rainnie and Paul Rosano (1974).

* That=E2=80=99s not what you=E2=80=99ll find yourself contemplating when y=
ou see Sleigh=E2=80=99s paintings, especially the works from the late =E2=
=80=9960s and early =E2=80=9970s, that dominate the show. It=E2=80=99s all =
hirsute figures in ornately patterned clothes set against densely patterned=
 backgrounds, or gardens in an impossible state of bloom. Sleigh is setting=
 men in academic poses as bathers, or grooming themselves in mirrors, or si=
mply as orientalist nudes=E2=80=94you know, odalisques. Formally, her work =
quotes art history; visually,
it=E2=80=99s the age of Aquarius.

What=E2=80=99s so cool about these works is not the =E2=80=9Creversal of ac=
ademic gender norms,=E2=80=9D as the gallery puts it in a press release tha=
t must have gotten jammed in the printer back in 2020. Instead, it=E2=80=99=
s the sense of time travel and transport that these paintings provide. New =
York in the 1970s was a scary and creatively propulsive place filled with e=
conomic and social anxiety. But you won=E2=80=99t see that in Sleigh=E2=80=
=99s paintings. Whether you get an erotic charge from her male or
female nudes is less important than getting a kick out of her models and th=
eir blissfully laid-back sense of themselves.=C2=A0

You can almost hear someone saying =E2=80=9CFar out!=E2=80=9D in the backgr=
ound. Which is even funnier when you realize, as the gallery reminds us, th=
at these ebullient works were painted in a New York art world dominated by =
coolly ironic pop art and a cerebral minimalism, neither of which is reflec=
ted in the work here.

* Cy Twombly at Maison d=E2=80=99Art in Los Angeles: The best gallery show =
I saw in Los Angeles last week had absolutely nothing to do with L.A.: Theo=
 Niarchos=E2=80=99s Maison d=E2=80=99Art ( https://maisondart.com/exhibitio=
ns/cy-twombly?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F28%2F25%29&utm=
_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F27%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_ac=
tion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) was hosting G=
erman doctor Reiner Speck=E2=80=99s collection of works by Cy Twombly. Dona=
ld Ryan, one of the curators, gave me a tour of Reiner Speck:
Fragments of an Adoration, which is one part Speck=E2=80=99s very personal =
take on Twombly, another part the story of the friendship between the artis=
t and collector.

Speck met Twombly after buying a painting, realizing it was unsigned, and d=
riving to Rome to find the artist and get it signed. Perhaps most important=
ly, their long-standing friendship was a meditation on the connection betwe=
en literature and art. Twombly=E2=80=99s classicism is well known. Speck=E2=
=80=99s fixation on
Proust and Petrarch, and his book collecting, led him to Twombly.

Ryan offers a catalogue essay about the importance of Romanticism in contem=
porary art that I found one of the more enlightening and enjoyable I=E2=80=
=99ve read in a while. But if you don=E2=80=99t want to get all bookish, th=
e show contains a number of letters Twombly wrote to Speck. Seeing Twombly=
=E2=80=99s loose, gestural handwriting beneath his works on paper can feel =
like a revelation. So much of Twombly=E2=80=99s
intensely personal art is better appreciated when some of that personality =
is revealed on airmail onion skin.

The show comes at a particularly interesting time in the art market. It wou=
ld be foolish to say that Twombly=E2=80=99s art has fallen out of favor. Bu=
t the current show at Gagosian in New York, and this exhibition in Los Ange=
les, are a reminder of the depth and variety of the artist=E2=80=99s work. =
The Maison d=E2=80=99Art show underscores the seriousness of Twombly=E2=80=
=99s project. His works don=E2=80=99t animate the
auction market to anywhere near the extent that they did a decade ago, when=
 auction sales peaked, or even four years ago, when they came close again. =
These shows are a reminder that Twombly may be primed for another run in th=
e near future.

