0;">That=E2=80=99s not what you=E2=80=99ll find yourself contemplating when=
 you see Sleigh=E2=80=99s paintings, especially the works from the late =E2=
=80=9960s and early =E2=80=9970s, that dominate the show. It=E2=80=99s all =
hirsute figures in ornately patterned clothes set against densely patterned=
 backgrounds, or gardens in an impossible state of bloom. Sleigh is setting=
 men in academic poses as bathers, or grooming themselves in mirrors, or si=
mply as orientalist nudes=E2=80=94you know, odalisques. Formally, her work =
quotes art history; visually,
it=E2=80=99s the age of Aquarius.<br/><br/>What=E2=80=99s so cool about the=
se works is not the =E2=80=9Creversal of academic gender norms,=E2=80=9D as=
 the gallery puts it in a press release that must have gotten jammed in the=
 printer back in 2020. Instead, it=E2=80=99s the sense of time travel and t=
ransport that these paintings provide. New York in the 1970s was a scary an=
d creatively propulsive place filled with economic and social anxiety. But =
you won=E2=80=99t see that in Sleigh=E2=80=99s paintings. Whether you get a=
n erotic charge from her male or
female nudes is less important than getting a kick out of her models and th=
eir blissfully laid-back sense of themselves.=C2=A0<br/><br/>You can almost=
 hear someone saying =E2=80=9CFar out!=E2=80=9D in the background. Which is=
 even funnier when you realize, as the gallery reminds us, that these ebull=
ient works were painted in a New York art world dominated by coolly ironic =
pop art and a cerebral minimalism, neither of which is reflected in the wor=
k here.=C2=A0=C2=A0</li></ul></div>
