and authenticity=E2=80=9D using =E2=80=9CAI and blockchain technology.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">One problem for any takeover plan has been=
 the stock price. The board fight had driven the stock to a recent high of =
=E2=82=AC8 per share. Even with the postmeeting drop to around =E2=82=AC6 p=
er share, the company has a market capitalization of around =E2=82=AC34 mil=
lion, which is a lot for a business with no profits and no clear path to pr=
ofitability.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In other words, there=E2=80=99s no w=
hite knight coming to save Artnet from itself. For decades, the company has=
 been plagued by fantasies of using its position as the standard database f=
or auction results to conquer the digital sales of art. But that really isn=
=E2=80=99t a friction point any longer. Galleries and auction houses are qu=
ite capable of selling art using the current tools at their disposal. Neith=
er Artnet nor Artsy
nor any of the several other businesses that have tried to create scale in =
the art market have succeeded. Wolff=E2=80=99s plan may involve rolling the=
m all up, but to what purpose?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">In fact, over the past decade, as we=E2=80=
=99ve discussed here more than once, the art market has remained flat or sh=
runk in real terms. That brutal fact has done more to break the dreams of d=
igital dominance than even the Neuendorfs=E2=80=99 hubris.</p></div>
